g.text: Image rectification
If both cameras faces the same direction...
1. The images are co-planar ->
the epipoles will be at infinity and the epipolar lines
will be parallel to each other and horizontal.
2. Correspondences search along horizontal scanlines (simpler!)
If the images are not in the required setup..
Trick: we can rewarp them through rotation, mapping both
image planes to a common plane parallel to the baseline.
This is called RECTIFICATION
However, for this rotation around the camera center, the 3D
structure must not be known.
Image rectification - Math
How can we make the epipolar lines horizontal?
(simplified example)
Rotation = Identity Matrix
Translation vector = move in the x direction
As Ki = I two corresponding points are related by
the epipolar constraint
Thus, y1 = y2, which means that the two images of
3D point x are on the same horizontal line
That expression must be
equal to 0 because it has to
satisfy the epipolar constraint
What if the previous setup is not the case?
we want to take an arbitrary setup
and rectify that
We have to align the x axis of the camera
coordinate system (virtual rotation)
r1,r2,r3 are the rows of the rotation matrix, where
r1 is pointing to the direction of the translation vector,
ans we normalize that to deal with unit vectors
r2 is the cross product of the c camera coordinate with r1
r3 must be the cross product of the previous two, otherwise
it won't be perpendicular
As the epipole in the first image is in the
direction of r1, it is easy to see that the
rotated epopole is ideal:
Thus, applying Rrect to the first camera leads to parallel
and horizontal lines
